Problem:
A university must schedule exams so that:
No student has overlapping exams.
Room capacities are sufficient.
Available time slots are used efficiently.

Constraints:
1.Student Conflict Constraint вЂ“ Exams with common students cannot be scheduled at the same time.
2.Room Capacity Constraint вЂ“ Number of students must not exceed room capacity.
3.Time Slot Constraint вЂ“ Only a limited number of time slots are available.

Commands / Algorithm Steps
1.Start.
2.Create a graph where each exam is a vertex.
3.Draw an edge between exams that have common students.
4.Select an uncolored exam.
5.Assign a time slot (color) to the exam.
6.Check if any adjacent exam has the same color.
7.Check room capacity for the assigned slot.
8.If constraints are satisfied, keep the assignment.
9.Move to the next exam.
10.If a conflict occurs, remove the assignment (backtrack).
11.Try another time slot.
12.Repeat until all exams are assigned time slots.
13.Display the final exam timetable.
14.Stop.

Pruning:
1.Reject a time slot if an adjacent exam already uses it.
2.Reject assignments that exceed room capacity.
3.Schedule highly conflicting exams first to reduce search space.

State Space Representation:
  Exam A в†’ Slot 1
  Exam B в†’ Slot 2
  Exam C в†’ Slot 1
  Exam D в†’ Slot 3

Complexity:
1.Time Complexity: O(kвЃї)
k = number of time slots
n = number of exams
2.Space Complexity: O(n)

Classification:
P: Problems solvable in polynomial time.
NP: Solutions verifiable in polynomial time.
NP-Complete: Exam Timetabling (modeled as Graph Coloring).

Justification:
Backtracking assigns time slots while checking conflicts and room capacities.
Graph coloring ensures that conflicting exams receive different time slots, producing a 
feasible and conflict-free exam schedule.
